this is not a problem of one or
another country.

29:47.519 --> 29:49.154 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is a global problem.

29:49.187 --> 29:53.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Just like -- think of epidemics
or think of
climate change.

29:53.392 --> 29:57.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think there is a growing
realization that
these are global issues, global
problems that

29:58.030 --> 30:04.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
affect the whole of humanity,
and only working
together we can address the root
causes, we

30:04.069 --> 30:08.740 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
can address what pushes people
to move on.

30:08.774 --> 30:14.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I think that there is a
necessity and not
just a moral commitment to do
that.

30:14.146 --> 30:17.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I want to ask
you a little
bit about some of the headwinds
that are facing

30:17.749 --> 30:20.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the U.N. and all the nations who
are grappling
with this.

30:20.952 --> 30:28.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We saw in Germany a very big
welcome mat thrown
out, and now we have seen the
rise of a far-right

30:28.160 --> 30:30.495 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
nationalistic party in response.

30:30.529 --> 30:36.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Here in the U.S., we have also
seen a very
strong anti-immigrant sentiment,
driven mostly

30:36.201 --> 30:37.636 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
out of fears of terrorism.

30:37.669 --> 30:39.604 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm curious.

30:39.638 --> 30:42.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you're talking to leaders
of world nations,
what do you tell them about
those sentiments?

30:42.674 --> 30:46.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How do we counter those, and
where do those
feelings lead?

30:46.044 --> 30:50.582 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FILIPPO GRANDI: I think there
are always two
sentiments in every society.

30:50.615 --> 30:52.284 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There is solidarity.

30:52.317 --> 30:56.588 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we have seen it very much in
Europe when
refugees arrive.

30:56.621 --> 31:00.225 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there is also a feeling of
apprehension
and rejection.

31:00.258 --> 31:06.298 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what people are, I think,
worried about
is when they see that the
response to these

31:06.331 --> 31:11.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
flows is not orderly, is not
organized, is
not structured.

31:11.069 --> 31:16.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is why this declaration
also invites
everybody, all the states,
together with the

31:16.942 --> 31:22.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
United Nations organization, to
work on these
responses, to make them more
predictable,

31:22.047 --> 31:23.815 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
more cooperative.

31:23.849 --> 31:29.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If Europe had reacted in that
manner back
last year, when people started
arriving in

31:29.287 --> 31:35.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
large numbers, I'm persuaded
that there wouldn't
have been such a negative
reaction growing

31:35.727 --> 31:41.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with the passage of time, that
people would
have accepted that it was
important, necessary,

31:41.500 --> 31:48.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
principled, but also possible to
receive refugees,
to give them asylum, people
fleeing from war

31:48.640 --> 31:49.608 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and persecution.

31:49.641 --> 31:51.843 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But we need to organize that
response better.

31:51.877 --> 31:55.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this is what -- this is the
value of this
declaration.

31:55.046 --> 31:57.682 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It will help us work towards
that organization.

31:57.716 --> 32:01.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It will give us the resources
hopefully to
do that.

32:01.086 --> 32:05.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The issue of
resettlement
is obviously a crucial one,
finding a more

32:05.190 --> 32:09.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
permanent home for these people,
so they're
not living in camps in
perpetuity.

32:09.594 --> 32:14.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the agreement today that was
-- the original
draft of that agreement asks for
a 10 percent

32:14.800 --> 32:19.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
annual rate of resettlement of
the refugees,
but that was scrapped because of
resistance

32:19.304 --> 32:21.273 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
from many of the donor nations.

32:21.306 --> 32:27.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if 10 percent per year
resettlement is
considered too much, what does
that tell you

32:27.179 --> 32:28.213 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
about the future?

32:28.246 --> 32:32.651 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FILIPPO GRANDI: This is a United
Nations document.

32:32.684 --> 32:37.622 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To issue this document, member
states have
to agree, all of them, 193.

32:37.656 --> 32:39.825 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
This is very difficult.

32:39.858 --> 32:45.463 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
So, there couldn't be an
agreement on a percentage
of refugees to be resettled.

32:45.497 --> 32:52.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But resettlement as a key
solution, especially
for the most vulnerable people,
is in the

32:52.103 --> 32:56.508 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
declaration as one of the things
that we need
to work on.

32:56.541 --> 33:02.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the declaration is the
preamble to a global
compact that we hope we will be
able to issue

33:02.647 --> 33:03.615 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in two years' time.

33:03.648 --> 33:05.584 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And during this time, we will
work.

33:05.617 --> 33:07.719 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We will work on these concrete
commitments.

33:07.752 --> 33:12.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't know if we will come up
with a figure,
but I think that what we must do
is increase

33:12.224 --> 33:14.359 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the present very low percentage.

33:14.392 --> 33:16.228 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We are talking about 10 percent.

33:16.261 --> 33:20.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Right now, it's less than 1
percent of the
refugees that are resettled.

33:20.498 --> 33:22.467 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So we need to improve on that.

33:22.500 --> 33:25.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Just very
quickly, I'm curious
about the financial status of
your organization.

33:25.871 --> 33:31.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We saw requests go out last year
for $20 billion,
and only half of that was
returned.

33:31.376 --> 33:35.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How able are you financially to
deal with
this crisis going forward this
year and into

33:35.580 --> 33:37.249 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the years into the future?

33:37.282 --> 33:42.954 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FILIPPO GRANDI: This has been a
chronic problem
for us humanitarian
organizations.

33:42.988 --> 33:49.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
UNHCR, my organization, has a
budget of $7
billion, in fact, annually, and
we receive

33:49.361 --> 33:52.297 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about 50, 55 percent of this
money.

33:52.330 --> 33:57.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once again, this is another
important element
of what was decided in New York
today.

33:57.535 --> 34:03.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was decided that the response
to refugee
flows shouldn't simply be
humanitarian, should

34:03.475 --> 34:08.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
involve big development actors,
like the World
Bank, who made very strong
commitments today.

34:08.747 --> 34:13.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that will bring new, fresh
resources,
different resources to the
table.

34:13.351 --> 34:15.420 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I hope that that will also
be a big progress.

34:15.453 --> 34:18.857 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Filippo Grandi,
U.N. high commissioner for
refugees, thanks

34:18.890 --> 34:20.292 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
very much for being here.

34:20.325 --> 34:26.031 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
FILIPPO GRANDI: Thank you.

34:26.064 --> 34:40.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Almost everyone
agrees American
politics has become more chaotic
in recent

34:40.078 --> 34:43.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
years, that it's changed, and
not always for
the better.

34:43.782 --> 34:48.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Scholar Jonathan Rauch has a
theory about
why, and he shares it in a
recent article

34:48.320 --> 34:49.988 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for "The Atlantic" magazine.

34:50.021 --> 34:53.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JONATHAN RAUCH, "The Atlantic":
The article
is about what I call chaos
syndrome.

34:53.425 --> 34:59.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is the steady decline
in the ability
of the political systems to
organize itself

34:59.431 --> 35:02.067 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
whether in campaigns, or in
government.

35:02.100 --> 35:05.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
People think that politics just
somehow magically
organizes itself.

35:05.470 --> 35:07.238 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It doesn't work that way.

35:07.272 --> 35:15.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You need to assemble these huge
coalitions
of 535 politicians on Capitol
Hill, and tens

35:15.313 --> 35:21.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of thousands of interest groups,
and tens
of millions of voters, and
assemble all those

35:21.286 --> 35:24.022 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in government to get stuff done.

35:24.055 --> 35:29.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That requires a lot of middlemen
and a lot
of people in between doing a lot
of bargaining

35:29.427 --> 35:30.462 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and negotiation.

35:30.495 --> 35:34.265 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You cut those people out, you
get chaos.

35:34.299 --> 35:39.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What we have done over the last
40 or 50 years
is systematically attacked and
weakened the

35:39.704 --> 35:44.642 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
parties, the political machines,
the professionals,
and insiders, and hacks, and all
the tools

35:44.676 --> 35:49.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that they use to get politicians
to play well
together.

35:49.514 --> 35:51.649 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And with those gone, you get
chaos.

35:51.683 --> 36:00.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What was it that
worked about
what you see as the kind of
ideal or close-to-ideal

36:00.125 --> 36:02.627 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
political system in this
country?

36:02.660 --> 36:08.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JONATHAN RAUCH: Starting in,
really, the very
beginning of the republic, we
began building

36:08.700 --> 36:15.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
parties with political machines
and hierarchies
and things like seniority
systems on Capitol

36:15.473 --> 36:16.775 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Hill.

36:16.808 --> 36:19.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, there were people to call
when you had
to get stuff done.

36:19.310 --> 36:26.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if Judy needed Jonathan to
vote on a bill
in Congress to keep the
government open or

36:26.751 --> 36:32.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
raise the debt limit or do
something for the
team, Judy could call me up and
say, you know,

36:32.657 --> 36:37.662 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if you do that, you're going to
get money
for your campaign, you're going
to have an

36:37.695 --> 36:42.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
easy reelection campaign, you're
going to
get that extra runway for the
airport in your

36:42.867 --> 36:47.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
district, we're going to be able
to make this
deal behind closed doors.

36:47.272 --> 36:48.873 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You could do all that stuff.

36:48.907 --> 36:52.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Virtually all of that stuff now
is difficult
or impossible.

36:52.210 --> 36:56.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And all you can do is beg me,
and I say, why
should I do any of that?

36:56.781 --> 36:58.917 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's just going to get me in
trouble in my
district.

36:58.950 --> 37:00.718 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Here we are.

37:00.752 --> 37:07.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Why were those
transactional
relationships important to make
government

37:07.725 --> 37:09.527 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
work, to make politics work in
this country?

37:09.561 --> 37:11.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JONATHAN RAUCH: The transactions
allow for
compromise.

37:11.563 --> 37:16.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And compromise is what it's got
to be all
about when you're governing,
because no one

37:16.501 --> 37:20.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is ever going to have a big
enough majority
to just do what they want to do
all the time.

37:20.605 --> 37:23.908 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Well, to get people to
compromise, you have
to give them stuff.

37:23.942 --> 37:30.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A famous example of this, but
far from the
only one, is the 1964 civil
rights bill, only

37:30.515 --> 37:35.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
passed because Lyndon Johnson
bought support
from Republicans.

37:35.620 --> 37:41.159 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He went to them and said, what
do you need
to put this bill through?

37:41.192 --> 37:47.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the Republican leader in the
House, a
man by the name of Charlie
Halleck, said,

37:47.198 --> 37:52.370 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
well, how about a big fat
research grant for
my district in Indiana?

37:52.403 --> 37:54.506 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
LBJ said done.

37:54.539 --> 37:55.507 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Halleck said done.

37:55.540 --> 37:56.508 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That bill went through.

37:56.541 --> 37:58.042 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

37:58.076 --> 37:59.544 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLIE HALLECK (R), Indiana:
God damn it,
did I help you on civil rights?

37:59.577 --> 38:01.079 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LYNDON BAINES JOHNSON, President
of the United
States: Yes, you sure did.

38:01.112 --> 38:03.314 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you helped yourself, because
you all want
civil rights as much as we do.

38:03.348 --> 38:06.050 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I believe it's a nonpartisan
bill.

38:06.084 --> 38:07.051 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't think it's a Johnson
bill.

38:07.085 --> 38:08.052 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

38:08.086 --> 38:09.120 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHARLIE HALLECK: Oh, no, no, no.

38:09.154 --> 38:10.054 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You're going to get all the
political advantage.

38:10.088 --> 38:11.055 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LYNDON BAINES JOHNSON: No, no,
no, no.

38:11.089 --> 38:12.290 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

38:12.323 --> 38:13.158 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLIE HALLECK: We aren't going
to get a
God-damned thing.

38:13.191 --> 38:14.058 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JONATHAN RAUCH: Is that
dishonorable?

38:14.092 --> 38:15.059 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
No, it's politics.

38:15.093 --> 38:16.060 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Is it pretty?

38:16.094 --> 38:17.862 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
No, it's politics.

38:17.896 --> 38:21.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But that's the kind of lubricant
that you
need to give people incentives
to work together.

38:21.799 --> 38:28.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And all of this
entails a measure
of secrecy behind closed doors,
smoke-filled

38:28.373 --> 38:29.340 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
rooms.

38:29.374 --> 38:31.109 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JONATHAN RAUCH: Smoke-filled
rooms.

38:31.142 --> 38:34.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we have come
to believe
in this country, by 2016, that
transparency

38:34.779 --> 38:37.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is good, that we need to know
everything,
open books, open doors.

38:37.682 --> 38:39.350 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JONATHAN RAUCH: Yes, put them in
the fishbowl.

38:39.384 --> 38:44.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, of course, the problem with
that is,
if every negotiation is
conducted in public,

38:44.122 --> 38:49.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then the minute one person says,
well, what
if we try this, next thing you
know, the interest

38:49.060 --> 38:52.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
groups have piled all in, and
the political
opponents have shot it to
pieces.

38:52.697 --> 38:54.499 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Fast-forward.

38:54.532 --> 39:00.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
president Obama is in office,
and he's trying
to get his health care reform
legislation

39:00.438 --> 39:01.673 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
proposal through.

39:01.706 --> 39:06.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JONATHAN RAUCH: Obama, of
course, campaigns
on sunshine.

39:06.311 --> 39:08.913 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're going to have the whole
process be open
to the public.

39:08.947 --> 39:15.553 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He gets into office and
discovers it is not
possible to write a very
complicated piece

39:15.587 --> 39:21.659 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of legislation involving
hundreds, if not
thousands of interest groups,
and multiple

39:21.693 --> 39:22.660 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
working parts.

39:22.694 --> 39:24.128 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You can't negotiate that in
public.

39:24.162 --> 39:26.197 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You will be shot to pieces on
day one.

39:26.231 --> 39:27.699 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So what does he do?

39:27.732 --> 39:32.870 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He goes behind closed doors, not
because he
wants to, but because he has to.

39:32.904 --> 39:37.909 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you open the doors, the
negotiations often
die before they even start.

39:37.942 --> 39:41.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you're saying
he -- you
know, for him, it never would
have gotten

39:41.479 --> 39:43.448 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
-- it barely passed, but it...

39:43.481 --> 39:44.415 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

39:44.449 --> 39:45.683 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JONATHAN RAUCH: It wouldn't have
gotten done.

39:45.717 --> 39:46.484 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States:
We are done.

39:46.517 --> 39:48.152 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

39:48.186 --> 39:49.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: President Obama's
crowning
legislative achievement came
early in his

39:49.621 --> 39:52.357 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
first term, in 2010.

39:52.390 --> 39:55.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Soon after, Democrats lost their
majority
in the House.

39:55.960 --> 40:01.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then, in 2011, the president
attempted to
negotiate the so-called grand
bargain budget

40:01.966 --> 40:05.637 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
bill with Republican House
Speaker John Boehner.

40:05.670 --> 40:07.705 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This time, the results were
different.

40:07.739 --> 40:14.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JONATHAN RAUCH: We were really
this close
to a very good budget deal in
which both parties,

40:14.479 --> 40:18.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and conservatives, and liberals,
were all
going to give something, and we
would have

40:18.383 --> 40:24.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
substantially reduced long-term
deficits,
reduced entitlement spending,
raised taxes

40:24.689 --> 40:30.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some, the kind of package that
ultimately
pretty much everyone agrees
we're going to

40:30.295 --> 40:34.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have to do in order to solve our
long-term
fiscal problems.

40:34.265 --> 40:39.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The speaker of the House, John
Boehner, wanted
to do it, but he could not get
his own caucus

40:39.704 --> 40:42.473 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
organized enough to back him up
on it.

40:42.507 --> 40:48.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's when I realized that
the groups
of obstructionists were now able
to basically

40:48.613 --> 40:50.648 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
hold the system to ransom.

40:50.682 --> 40:56.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, in 2013, GOP
leaders could
not prevent their renegade
members from shutting

40:56.954 --> 40:58.756 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
down the federal government.

40:58.790 --> 41:03.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JONATHAN RAUCH: No one wants it
to shut down,
including a lot of the people
who voted to

41:03.528 --> 41:04.495 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
shut it down.

41:04.529 --> 41:06.230 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They were kind of hoping that
wouldn't happen.

41:06.264 --> 41:09.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ted Cruz wanted to shut it down
because it
was good for his presidential
campaign.

41:09.500 --> 41:10.568 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

41:10.601 --> 41:12.337 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TED CRUZ (R), Texas: Do you like
green eggs
and ham?

41:12.370 --> 41:18.109 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JONATHAN RAUCH: So, John
Boehner, appearing
on the Leno show, and Leno says,
why did the

41:18.142 --> 41:19.444 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
government shut down?

41:19.477 --> 41:22.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Boehner says something
that's stuck in
my mind ever since:

41:22.246 --> 41:23.981 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

41:24.015 --> 41:25.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN BOEHNER (R-OH), Speaker of
the House:
A leader without followers is
simply a man

41:25.550 --> 41:27.318 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
taking a walk.

41:27.352 --> 41:29.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JONATHAN RAUCH: This is the
speaker of the
House who no longer has enough
incentives,

41:29.887 --> 41:33.791 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
enough tools, enough
organizational power
to get people to follow.

41:33.825 --> 41:36.627 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We don't have a crisis of
leadership in Washington,
Judy.

41:36.661 --> 41:38.196 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We have a crisis of
followership.

41:38.229 --> 41:41.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: When did things
start to go
wrong, in your view?

41:41.766 --> 41:49.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, when did the system that
was working
so great, with the patronage,
with pork, when

41:49.107 --> 41:50.875 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
did it start to change?

41:50.908 --> 41:54.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JONATHAN RAUCH: Well, caveat, I
don't want
anyone to think it's just all
the golden age

41:54.846 --> 41:56.314 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and everything was perfect.

41:56.347 --> 41:59.016 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There were big problems with
every system,
and there always have been.

41:59.050 --> 42:01.452 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's a question of
overcorrecting.

42:01.486 --> 42:06.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The needle went too far one way,
so we overcorrected
and went way too far in the
other, threw the

42:06.090 --> 42:07.792 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
baby out with the bathwater.

42:07.825 --> 42:12.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Some of this must
have been
in reaction to Watergate, to
Vietnam, the

42:12.764 --> 42:18.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Pentagon Papers, the idea the
government lied
to the American people, so the
desire was

42:18.035 --> 42:19.804 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to fix that.

42:19.837 --> 42:23.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JONATHAN RAUCH: That and the
idealism of a
generation which was, in many
ways, to its

42:23.474 --> 42:29.113 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
credit, very idealistic, and
said, well, surely
we can do it better than that.

42:29.147 --> 42:31.315 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They start passing a whole
series of reforms.

42:31.349 --> 42:34.419 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, we moved to direct primary
elections.

42:34.452 --> 42:37.488 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We started reducing the role of
appropriations
committees.

42:37.522 --> 42:40.525 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We started tearing down the
seniority system
on Capitol Hill.

42:40.558 --> 42:42.460 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
All of that begins in the '70s.

42:42.493 --> 42:46.364 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It accelerates and continues in
the '90s,
and it's going on to this day.

42:46.397 --> 42:51.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Moving toward, I
guess, what
some people would describe as
small-D democratic

42:51.035 --> 42:53.471 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
politics, where more and more
people are involved?

42:53.504 --> 42:57.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JONATHAN RAUCH: Well, that was
the ideal,
but it didn't work out that way,
of course.

42:57.108 --> 43:02.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As you know, the number of
people who actually
vote in primaries is very small.

43:02.046 --> 43:08.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Donald Trump basically clinched
the nomination
with the support of about 12
percent of Republican

43:08.920 --> 43:10.721 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
voters.

43:10.755 --> 43:15.059 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's about it, because it
turns out that,
when you remove these
intermediaries, these

43:15.092 --> 43:19.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
political professionals from the
system, who
you really empower are the small
minorities

43:19.997 --> 43:25.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of activists who are best
organized, and either
most passionate, or have the
narrowest parochial

43:25.203 --> 43:26.671 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
interests, but you kind of turn
it over to
them.

43:26.704 --> 43:28.539 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And has that
happened in both
parties?

43:28.573 --> 43:29.807 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JONATHAN RAUCH: Yes.

43:29.841 --> 43:31.676 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Both parties are structurally
weak.

43:31.709 --> 43:37.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Look, Judy, this is the first
time in my life
-- and I'm 56 years old --
where, of the four

43:37.815 --> 43:45.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
final finishers -- set aside
John Kasich -- three
of them were renegades who had
run as outsiders

43:45.690 --> 43:51.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and against their own party
structures, Bernie
Sanders, not even a Democrat,
Donald Trump,

43:51.896 --> 43:54.632 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in no meaningful sense a
Republican.

43:54.665 --> 44:00.605 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Ted Cruz shut down the
government, hurt his
own party, campaigned against
his own leadership.

44:00.638 --> 44:06.177 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Parties and political systems
used to be about
excluding renegades who would
never play well

44:06.210 --> 44:07.845 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
with others in government.

44:07.879 --> 44:12.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now it's actually systematically
screening
them in.

44:12.083 --> 44:13.818 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's new.

44:13.851 --> 44:17.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it's very important for
my friends
who are Democrats who are kind
of thinking,

44:17.154 --> 44:20.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
well, Hillary Clinton will win,
and then the
Republicans will get their act
together, problem

44:20.658 --> 44:21.626 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
solved.

44:21.659 --> 44:24.962 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I say, no, Donald Trump didn't
cause chaos.

44:24.996 --> 44:26.764 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Chaos caused Trump.

44:26.797 --> 44:31.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There will be more coming
afterwards if we
don't re-empower politicians to
get organized

44:31.869 --> 44:37.074 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and work together.

44:37.108 --> 44:50.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Finally tonight: The
14th librarian
of Congress was sworn in last
week to lead

44:50.087 --> 44:54.625 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
one of the nation's oldest
institutions into
its next chapter.

44:54.659 --> 44:57.895 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown visited Carla
Hayden as she
began her new position.

44:57.929 --> 45:03.501 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It is the largest
library in
the world.

45:03.534 --> 45:10.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Founded in 1800, with some 162
million items,
the Library of Congress in
Washington, D.C.,

45:10.508 --> 45:16.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is a repository of books, yes,
but also a
storehouse of history and
culture, filled

45:16.314 --> 45:22.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with recordings, photographs,
maps and manuscripts,
charged with preserving national
treasures

45:22.119 --> 45:23.688 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of all kinds.

45:23.721 --> 45:26.123 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The new librarian of Congress is
Carla Hayden.

45:26.157 --> 45:27.458 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why did you want to take on this
job?

45:27.491 --> 45:30.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CARLA HAYDEN, Librarian of
Congress: It's
a librarian's dream.

45:31.028 --> 45:39.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in the field, it's seen as a
job that
really epitomizes what libraries
can mean

45:39.870 --> 45:41.572 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and symbolize.

45:41.606 --> 45:46.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this library can really help
libraries
throughout the country show the
worth of a

45:46.777 --> 45:48.112 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
library and a community.

45:48.145 --> 45:50.915 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It's pretty
spectacular new
digs, though, for you.

45:50.948 --> 45:51.916 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

45:51.949 --> 45:53.718 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CARLA HAYDEN: Well, it is quite
something.

45:53.751 --> 45:58.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It really makes you realize what
this library
symbolizes, to be at the seat of
government.

45:58.956 --> 46:03.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: While most of the
past 13 heads
of this historic institution
have come from

46:03.828 --> 46:09.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
scholarly backgrounds, Carla
Hayden is a librarian
through and through, and a
strong advocate

46:09.800 --> 46:12.103 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for their continuing relevance.

46:12.136 --> 46:17.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She headed the Enoch Pratt Free
Library in
Baltimore since 1993, and before
that worked

46:17.742 --> 46:24.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the Chicago Public Library,
a career coinciding
with enormous changes in
information technology.

46:24.348 --> 46:29.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARLA HAYDEN: Technology has
such an impact
on libraries in the last 20
years, and the

46:29.186 --> 46:31.355 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
last 10 years in particular.

46:31.389 --> 46:42.299 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The opportunity to make those
items available
online for everyone is daunting,
but also

46:42.333 --> 46:43.801 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
exciting.

46:43.834 --> 46:47.438 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's a pivotal time to think
about what
could be done with technology.

46:47.471 --> 46:52.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: This is where the
library has
been hit with criticism, though,
in several

46:52.943 --> 46:58.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
independent assessments, that it
has fallen
behind, has not modernized its
technology,

46:58.215 --> 47:00.951 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has not digitized much of its
collection.

47:00.985 --> 47:02.820 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is that a fair assessment?

47:02.853 --> 47:09.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARLA HAYDEN: It's an assessment
that I believe
reflects the fact that, with the
largest library

47:09.860 --> 47:17.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the world, 162 million items,
that's a
pretty substantial amount of
material to digitize.

47:17.735 --> 47:22.173 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there's a lot involved with
these rare
and unique materials.

47:22.206 --> 47:26.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In the bowels of
the library,
we were shown part of that
effort, a scanner

47:26.410 --> 47:32.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that can photograph 200 pages an
hour, here,
a delicate Persian history book
dating to

47:32.149 --> 47:33.918 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
1825.

47:33.951 --> 47:38.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But these are still initial
steps to make
more accessible a collection
said to stretch

47:38.589 --> 47:42.093 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
over 863 miles of bookshelves.

47:42.126 --> 47:45.162 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In your life, in your career,
you have had
to defend libraries, right?

47:45.196 --> 47:46.163 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CARLA HAYDEN: Yes.

47:46.197 --> 47:47.164 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

47:47.198 --> 47:48.299 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I have had...

47:48.332 --> 47:50.201 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Why should we
give you money,
right?

47:50.234 --> 47:55.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARLA HAYDEN: Why should you
invest in a library,
especially a library building,
in the time

47:55.239 --> 47:57.875 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the digital age?

47:57.908 --> 48:04.281 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What we found is a library's
place is even
more important.

48:04.315 --> 48:11.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a hunger in this
digital age to hear
authors together, to participate
in programs,

48:11.655 --> 48:14.658 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to just be in a place, a
community space.

48:14.692 --> 48:19.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I asked Carla
Hayden if she
worries about the privatization
of digital

48:19.897 --> 48:21.999 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
media from companies such as
Google.

48:22.032 --> 48:28.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARLA HAYDEN: It can be a
public-private partnership,
and there's room and space for
everyone.

48:28.606 --> 48:34.211 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I get excited thinking about
those partnerships
and the opportunities.

48:34.245 --> 48:40.384 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are so many items that are
not in the
copyright domain.

48:40.417 --> 48:45.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And people might not realize the
Library of
Congress manages the copyright
process for

48:45.556 --> 48:47.324 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the nation.

48:47.358 --> 48:55.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you do have items that are
available to
be digitized that a partner
could help quite

48:55.399 --> 48:56.834 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a bit.

48:56.867 --> 48:58.736 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You have also
been known as
a privacy advocate, right?

48:58.769 --> 49:03.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As the president of the American
Library Association
in 2003, you argued against some
aspects of

49:04.008 --> 49:06.043 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the Patriot Act.

49:06.076 --> 49:13.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are you worried still about
government surveillance
of information, even what's
available at libraries,

49:13.651 --> 49:15.452 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
government watching what people
read?

49:15.486 --> 49:20.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARLA HAYDEN: Librarians were
called during
that time feisty fighters for
freedom, and

49:20.090 --> 49:22.927 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we were very proud of that
label.

49:22.960 --> 49:29.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We were just concerned that, at
that time,
when people were rightfully
concerned about

49:29.800 --> 49:35.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
national security, that there
was a balance
with a person's right to know.

49:35.639 --> 49:41.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just because you're interested
in what jihad
is doesn't mean you intend to
join.

49:41.579 --> 49:45.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You don't think
Americans need
to be worried that, whether
they're checking

49:45.916 --> 49:49.286 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out a book, whether they're
going online to
search something?

49:49.320 --> 49:51.355 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
